1
00:00:10,540 --> 00:00:15,300
I deliver perfection...
and don't brag about it! :D

2
00:00:47,740 --> 00:00:51,580
Chris, what is it?

3
00:00:52,700 --> 00:00:56,500
I love you so much.

4
00:00:57,860 --> 00:01:00,940
Don't you love me any more?

5
00:01:12,740 --> 00:01:16,660
I've made progress,
and I recognise that.

6
00:01:16,900 --> 00:01:22,500
But my wife, who I can't
even convince to come here...

7
00:01:22,740 --> 00:01:26,300
Anything can set her off.
It could be the phone ringing,

8
00:01:26,540 --> 00:01:30,500
something on the news,
something online, going shopping maybe.

9
00:01:30,740 --> 00:01:35,220
A commemorative T-shirt in the window.
Itjust puts her right back in that place,

10
00:01:35,460 --> 00:01:40,380
and it's like all my progress - ripped away.
And I'm right back there with her.

11
00:01:40,620 --> 00:01:45,700
I feel totally the opposite. I see the TV
and I see the Internet and I see those T-shirts

12
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:51,940
and I feel nothing. The more I see the images,
the less I feel, the less I believe that it's real.

13
00:01:52,180 --> 00:01:58,180
I mean, I think I'm supposed to feel
something by now. Don't you think so?

14
00:02:00,060 --> 00:02:03,580
Linda, this is Chris Kelvin.
I'm returning your call.

15
00:02:03,820 --> 00:02:06,740
I have two times available this week;

16
00:02:06,980 --> 00:02:11,780
7am on Tuesday
or 6.15pm on Thursday.

17
00:02:12,020 --> 00:02:18,540
You can leave a message if either
of those times are good for you. Thank you.

18
00:02:18,780 --> 00:02:21,340
Well, I know that's not true.

19
00:02:21,580 --> 00:02:26,260
Because I know you, and I know it's not true.

20
00:02:30,660 --> 00:02:33,100
Good. I'm glad.

21
00:02:33,340 --> 00:02:34,980
All right.

22
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:39,180
Let's pick this up on Wednesday.

23
00:03:40,420 --> 00:03:42,860
Can I help you?

24
00:03:43,100 --> 00:03:47,380
<i>We're looking for Dr Chris Kelvin.</i>

25
00:03:51,340 --> 00:03:54,420
<i>Chris...</i>

26
00:03:55,660 --> 00:04:00,420
<i>I can't imagine what you must be
thinking, getting a message like this.</i>

27
00:04:00,660 --> 00:04:07,380
<i>I apologise if it seems melodramatic, but
you are the only person I can... I can trust...</i>

28
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:10,860
<i>in the situation.</i>

29
00:04:11,100 --> 00:04:13,500
<i>I need your help.</i>

30
00:04:13,740 --> 00:04:16,260
<i>I need you to come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

31
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:20,300
<i>I don't know how to describe
what we are experiencing up here.</i>

32
00:04:20,540 --> 00:04:25,780
<i>We can't even agree amongst ourselves
what is... what is happening, or...</i>

33
00:04:26,020 --> 00:04:29,780
<i>what to do about it.</i>

34
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:36,380
<i>I suppose the... the most obvious
solution would be to leave.</i>

35
00:04:36,540 --> 00:04:43,220
<i>But none of us want to. That's why
you're getting this... this bizarre request.</i>

36
00:04:43,460 --> 00:04:46,260
<i>I...</i>

37
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:50,300
<i>I told the crew that your
background and experiences</i>

38
00:04:50,540 --> 00:04:55,580
<i>made you the...
the ideal candidate for this job.</i>

39
00:04:55,820 --> 00:04:58,020
<i>Don't worry. I didn't elaborate.</i>

40
00:04:59,780 --> 00:05:02,460
<i>But it's true.</i>

41
00:05:02,700 --> 00:05:06,180
<i>So, anyway...</i>

42
00:05:07,580 --> 00:05:10,940
<i>I, uh... I hope you will come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

43
00:05:11,180 --> 00:05:13,780
<i>I-I think you need to.</i>

44
00:05:14,020 --> 00:05:17,180
<i>You will see what I mean.</i>

45
00:05:17,420 --> 00:05:23,500
<i>I wish I could be more specific
about all of this, but... you know.</i>

46
00:05:23,900 --> 00:05:27,780
<i>People are listening.</i>

47
00:05:31,180 --> 00:05:37,300
You can imagine the distress
Dr Gibarian's message caused at DBA.

48
00:05:39,340 --> 00:05:41,700
Why not send in the security force?

49
00:05:41,940 --> 00:05:46,380
We did. We lost contact
as they were approaching Solaris.

50
00:05:46,620 --> 00:05:50,100
They haven't returned.

51
00:05:50,340 --> 00:05:53,100
There must be some
sort of on-board Al system.

52
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:55,140
They shut it down.

53
00:05:55,380 --> 00:05:59,500
The company was hoping to solve
this problem without involving a civilian.

54
00:05:59,740 --> 00:06:04,060
Obviously these are extreme circumstances.

55
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:07,900
Some preparation is involved
but you shouldn't have any trouble.

56
00:06:08,140 --> 00:06:14,420
The flight itself is fully automated.
You'll be asleep most of the trip.

57
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:22,340
We feel confident that if you board
the ship, you can negotiate their safe return.

58
00:06:22,580 --> 00:06:25,940
Is that what everybody wants?

59
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:29,660
Of course.

60
00:11:42,180 --> 00:11:46,020
Find the probability of F.

61
00:11:48,420 --> 00:11:52,380
OK, stop. Go back.

62
00:11:53,940 --> 00:11:57,420
Snow.

63
00:12:15,260 --> 00:12:18,460
Kelvin, is it?

64
00:12:18,700 --> 00:12:20,380
Yeah.

65
00:12:20,620 --> 00:12:24,340
Kelvin. Right. Oh, man.

66
00:12:24,580 --> 00:12:26,860
Sorry about that, Kelvin.

67
00:12:27,100 --> 00:12:29,100
Names, you know, just...

68
00:12:29,340 --> 00:12:31,460
For some reason. It, uh...

69
00:12:31,700 --> 00:12:34,100
Yeah. Uh...

70
00:12:34,340 --> 00:12:37,380
Well, uh, you wanna come in?

71
00:12:37,620 --> 00:12:39,700
I'm fine.

72
00:12:39,940 --> 00:12:44,860
Whose blood is that, leading to the lab?

73
00:12:45,020 --> 00:12:48,500
Yeah. Blood.

74
00:12:48,500 --> 00:12:51,980
How 'bout that?

75
00:12:54,940 --> 00:12:56,900
Katarn.

76
00:12:57,140 --> 00:12:59,020
He, um... Yeah.

77
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:04,180
Security forces showed up
and he just took off, and they...

78
00:13:04,420 --> 00:13:07,660
Yeah. Put a hole in his pot.

79
00:13:07,900 --> 00:13:11,660
What happened to Gibarian?

80
00:13:12,780 --> 00:13:14,620
Yeah.

81
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:18,660
It was a suicide.

82
00:13:19,660 --> 00:13:21,380
Who found him?

83
00:13:21,620 --> 00:13:24,540
I found him.

84
00:13:24,780 --> 00:13:27,900
What happened to Rhys?

85
00:13:28,140 --> 00:13:30,620
Yeah, now, Rhys w... Huh.

86
00:13:30,860 --> 00:13:34,940
We don't know, because the thing is,
he kind of... disappeared.

87
00:13:35,180 --> 00:13:36,940
- Disappeared?
- Disappeared.

88
00:13:37,180 --> 00:13:41,660
- How did he disappear?
- Exactly.

89
00:13:42,100 --> 00:13:45,220
Don't know. We do know
that he's not on the ship, uh,

90
00:13:45,460 --> 00:13:49,620
and that's... that's all we know.

91
00:13:49,860 --> 00:13:52,220
Where's Dr Gordon?

92
00:13:52,460 --> 00:13:55,940
Dr Gordon. She is in her room,

93
00:13:56,180 --> 00:13:57,860
and, um...

94
00:13:58,100 --> 00:14:02,380
Dr Gordon won't let you in her room.

95
00:14:06,460 --> 00:14:10,940
Can you tell me what's happening here?

96
00:14:11,460 --> 00:14:13,740
I could tell you what's happening,

97
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:16,620
but, uh...

98
00:14:16,860 --> 00:14:22,380
I don't know if that'd
really tell you what's happening.

99
00:14:28,060 --> 00:14:31,060
I just wanna talk to you.

100
00:14:31,300 --> 00:14:36,780
You have to give me your word
you won't try to come in.

101
00:14:39,620 --> 00:14:43,100
All right.

102
00:14:56,940 --> 00:14:58,660
Well?

103
00:14:58,900 --> 00:15:02,620
- What happened to Gibarian?
- Didn't you talk to Snow?

104
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:06,140
- I wanted to hear your version.
- There isn't any version.

105
00:15:06,380 --> 00:15:10,140
He killed himself.

106
00:15:10,860 --> 00:15:15,980
Why haven't you come home?
What happened here?

107
00:15:16,140 --> 00:15:20,100
What did you find?

108
00:15:20,260 --> 00:15:24,140
- Who are you representing?
- I'm the last effort to recover this mission,

109
00:15:24,380 --> 00:15:29,060
before they abandon this ship
and everyone on board.

110
00:15:37,340 --> 00:15:41,660
Until it starts happening to you,
there's really no point in discussing it.

111
00:16:04,340 --> 00:16:07,620
Hey.

112
00:16:13,580 --> 00:16:16,860
Hey!

113
00:16:31,020 --> 00:16:34,580
<i>- Who else is here?
- Who else is here?</i>

114
00:16:34,820 --> 00:16:38,300
<i>I saw a boy.</i>

115
00:16:41,140 --> 00:16:45,020
Gibarian's son.

116
00:16:45,420 --> 00:16:49,700
- Michael.
- How is that possible?

117
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:52,980
I think that's why you're here.

118
00:16:53,220 --> 00:16:56,820
I want a formal interview with you
and Gordon. I'll need your help with her.

119
00:16:57,060 --> 00:16:59,420
Yeah. All right.

120
00:16:59,660 --> 00:17:00,700
Um...

121
00:17:00,940 --> 00:17:03,180
How much sleep do you need, Kelvin?

122
00:17:03,420 --> 00:17:05,820
- How much sleep?
- Yeah.

123
00:17:06,060 --> 00:17:10,740
- How long can you go without sleep?
- Depends.

124
00:17:11,660 --> 00:17:12,860
Well,

125
00:17:13,100 --> 00:17:16,340
when you do go to sleep,

126
00:17:16,580 --> 00:17:21,540
I find I sleep much better
with the door locked.

127
00:17:23,820 --> 00:17:29,380
<i>I was with the project when it was
still with NASA, before it was sold to DBA.</i>

128
00:17:29,620 --> 00:17:31,580
I was trained in physics.

129
00:17:31,820 --> 00:17:36,260
I was sent here to assess
the economic potential of Solaris.

130
00:17:36,500 --> 00:17:42,140
Whether or not it was a viable commercial
property or possible energy source.

131
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:46,460
I was still compiling data
when this shit started happening.

132
00:17:46,700 --> 00:17:49,380
Did you run any tests
on the food, air, water?

133
00:17:49,620 --> 00:17:56,220
I checked it 50 times. There are no signs of
contaminants or psychotropic compounds.

134
00:17:58,220 --> 00:18:02,300
How about you? How are you doing?

135
00:18:03,260 --> 00:18:04,980
Depression.

136
00:18:05,220 --> 00:18:09,820
Along with bouts of hypomania
and primary insomnia.

137
00:18:10,060 --> 00:18:13,700
Suggestions of agoraphobia,
obsessive-compulsive disorder,

138
00:18:13,940 --> 00:18:15,980
shock, fatigue, denial...

139
00:18:16,220 --> 00:18:19,940
- Not unusual, given the circumstances.
- I know.

140
00:18:20,180 --> 00:18:26,060
All right. Now, what can you tell me
about what's happening here?

141
00:18:26,300 --> 00:18:31,580
Just that I want it to stop,
but I want to stop it.

142
00:18:31,820 --> 00:18:37,100
If I can stop it that means
I'm smarter than it is.

143
00:18:41,940 --> 00:18:47,020
You know you can go home,
walk away from all of this.

144
00:18:47,260 --> 00:18:51,140
I can guarantee it.

145
00:18:56,300 --> 00:18:58,580
Yeah.

146
00:18:58,820 --> 00:19:04,540
The thing is... Man, I would kill
to go back there. I'd... kill.

147
00:19:04,780 --> 00:19:07,220
But Gordon?

148
00:19:07,460 --> 00:19:12,140
Gordon happens to be Gordon, you know?

149
00:19:12,340 --> 00:19:15,820
So, um...

150
00:19:19,460 --> 00:19:22,860
But I'll see what I can do.

151
00:19:23,100 --> 00:19:27,380
<i>We take off into the cosmos.</i>

152
00:19:27,740 --> 00:19:32,740
<i>Ready for anything -
solitude, hardship, exhaustion...</i>

153
00:19:32,980 --> 00:19:36,060
<i>death.</i>

154
00:19:37,260 --> 00:19:39,220
<i>We're proud of ourselves.</i>

155
00:19:39,460 --> 00:19:44,940
<i>But when you think about it,
our enthusiasm's a sham.</i>

156
00:19:47,660 --> 00:19:52,740
<i>We don't want other worlds. We want mirrors.</i>

157
00:22:33,740 --> 00:22:36,540
So, anyway... How's the spawn?

158
00:22:36,780 --> 00:22:40,180
Oh, good, good. He cries
and shits in his pants every two hours.

159
00:22:40,420 --> 00:22:43,900
- I know the feeling.

160
00:22:44,140 --> 00:22:46,020
When are you leaving?

161
00:22:46,260 --> 00:22:49,780
- We've been postponed again.
- I didn't hear that.

162
00:22:50,020 --> 00:22:51,660
Nobody knows yet.

163
00:22:51,900 --> 00:22:56,100
The governments are looking for a buyer. I
wish we could tell people what's happening.

164
00:22:56,340 --> 00:22:58,460
You can tell me. I'm a doctor.

165
00:22:58,700 --> 00:23:02,500
Well, Doctor, as we study Solaris,

166
00:23:02,740 --> 00:23:06,700
the most interesting thing is it, um...

167
00:23:06,940 --> 00:23:11,460
Well, it seems to be reacting.
Almost like it knows it's being observed.

168
00:23:11,700 --> 00:23:14,260
We can't explain it.

169
00:23:14,500 --> 00:23:18,100
Are you listening to me? Chris?

170
00:23:19,500 --> 00:23:23,380
- So anyway...
- So anyway. Sorry.

171
00:23:23,620 --> 00:23:29,580
Go to her. Her name is Rheya. She's a bit
tricky but, um, I guess she's worthwhile.

172
00:23:29,820 --> 00:23:31,780
Maybe she needs a shrink.

173
00:23:32,020 --> 00:23:35,420
Don't we all?

174
00:24:18,420 --> 00:24:22,100
Don't blow it.

175
00:24:25,900 --> 00:24:27,460
<i>You start.</i>

176
00:24:27,700 --> 00:24:29,700
<i>I did.</i>

177
00:24:29,940 --> 00:24:31,500
<i>Really?</i>

178
00:24:31,740 --> 00:24:37,820
All right, I'm gonna resist the impulse
to ask you about the door knob.

179
00:24:37,940 --> 00:24:41,220
- Do you always resist your impulses?
- Not always.

180
00:24:43,060 --> 00:24:46,940
<i>Try poetry.</i>

181
00:24:47,300 --> 00:24:50,140
<i>"And death shall have no dominion."</i>

182
00:24:50,380 --> 00:24:53,980
<i>Mm. Thomas.</i>

183
00:24:54,220 --> 00:24:58,500
<i>It's not a very happy poem, though.</i>

184
00:24:58,580 --> 00:25:05,060
<i>Well, you didn't seem
very happy when I saw you on the train.</i>

185
00:25:08,140 --> 00:25:10,460
<i>I wasn't.</i>

186
00:25:10,700 --> 00:25:14,180
<i>And tonight?</i>

187
00:25:15,180 --> 00:25:18,820
<i>It's early.</i>

188
00:27:54,300 --> 00:27:57,780
Goddammit!

189
00:28:30,860 --> 00:28:33,260
I'm awake.

190
00:28:33,500 --> 00:28:36,780
Yes.

191
00:28:37,060 --> 00:28:39,100
How are you here?

192
00:28:39,340 --> 00:28:41,380
How are you here?

193
00:28:41,620 --> 00:28:44,980
How do you mean?

194
00:28:45,220 --> 00:28:51,740
Where do you think you are?
Where do you think you are right now?

195
00:28:52,100 --> 00:28:55,220
At home.

196
00:28:55,460 --> 00:28:59,340
Where is home?

197
00:28:59,660 --> 00:29:02,780
With you, where we live.

198
00:29:03,020 --> 00:29:09,900
And do you remember being anywhere else
with me? Being together anywhere else?

199
00:29:11,140 --> 00:29:15,620
- Our apartment.
- Describe it.

200
00:29:16,260 --> 00:29:20,540
It's dark. It's very very dark.

201
00:29:21,660 --> 00:29:25,700
And there are no paintings on the wall.

202
00:29:25,940 --> 00:29:29,220
No pictures anywhere.

203
00:29:29,460 --> 00:29:34,900
No pictures on the fridge, even,
which I always thought was a bit strange.

204
00:29:35,140 --> 00:29:40,380
Do you remember
where we first saw each other?

205
00:29:41,420 --> 00:29:45,100
On a train.

206
00:29:53,180 --> 00:29:56,260
Chris...

207
00:30:02,140 --> 00:30:06,100
I'm so happy to see you.

208
00:30:06,860 --> 00:30:10,780
I love you so much.

209
00:30:15,180 --> 00:30:19,460
Don't you love me any more?

210
00:30:22,620 --> 00:30:25,820
I have to check out something with the crew.

211
00:30:26,060 --> 00:30:27,620
No! No!

212
00:30:27,860 --> 00:30:32,820
- Don't leave me! Don't leave me!
- Why? Why?

213
00:30:33,860 --> 00:30:37,540
- Why?
- I don't know.

214
00:30:39,020 --> 00:30:42,500
I don't know.

215
00:30:44,620 --> 00:30:46,420
It's OK.

216
00:30:46,660 --> 00:30:50,140
It's OK.

217
00:30:58,300 --> 00:31:02,260
Why are you sitting over there?

218
00:31:05,500 --> 00:31:09,820
Can I come and sit with you?

219
00:32:18,540 --> 00:32:21,820
Hey.

220
00:32:24,620 --> 00:32:28,700
What was that?

221
00:32:30,420 --> 00:32:32,140
Yeah.

222
00:32:32,380 --> 00:32:35,580
How 'bout that?

223
00:32:35,820 --> 00:32:39,620
Still workin' on that.

224
00:32:42,420 --> 00:32:45,060
Where's your visitor?

225
00:32:45,300 --> 00:32:49,780
I don't know. Stopped appearing.

226
00:32:50,500 --> 00:32:54,780
- Who's your visitor?
- My brother.

227
00:33:12,860 --> 00:33:16,180
Who was it?

228
00:33:16,420 --> 00:33:19,900
My wife.

229
00:33:20,780 --> 00:33:23,860
Dead?

230
00:33:30,900 --> 00:33:34,860
So what was her name?

231
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:39,460
Will she come back?

232
00:33:44,620 --> 00:33:48,260
Do you want her to?

233
00:34:43,820 --> 00:34:45,540
- No, it isn't.
- Yes, it is.

234
00:34:45,780 --> 00:34:48,700
- No, it isn't. It's crap.
- Only one way to find out.

235
00:34:48,940 --> 00:34:52,100
You can submit it to someone
and see if they publish it.

236
00:34:52,340 --> 00:34:54,540
That's not an indication of anything.

237
00:34:54,780 --> 00:34:59,300
So no one else's opinion counts
except for yours?

238
00:34:59,540 --> 00:35:02,780
- Yeah.
- That's insane.

239
00:35:03,020 --> 00:35:05,220
- "That's" insane.
- I like it.

240
00:35:05,460 --> 00:35:09,740
Brings out the red in my eyes.

241
00:35:12,180 --> 00:35:15,220
So, did you show it to your father?

242
00:35:15,460 --> 00:35:17,100
- Yeah.
- And?

243
00:35:17,340 --> 00:35:19,700
- And he liked it.
- What'd he say?

244
00:35:19,940 --> 00:35:23,900
- He said he liked it.
- Well...

245
00:35:24,300 --> 00:35:29,740
He's a man who doesn't pass out
compliments very easily. That's something.

246
00:35:29,980 --> 00:35:33,500
- What's that tell you?
- Can we talk about something else? Please?

247
00:35:33,740 --> 00:35:38,020
All right. When do you wanna get hitched?

248
00:35:40,460 --> 00:35:45,180
Every time I bring it up
you make ajoke about it, and...

249
00:35:45,420 --> 00:35:49,500
I know, I know. That's pathet...
I'm sorry. It's just...

